  "prompt_text": "Derive the quadratic formula from the general form ax^2 + bx + c = 0.",
  "response_text": "To derive the quadratic formula from the general form of a quadratic equation ax^2 + bx + c = 0, we will complete the square.\n\n1. First, we need to rewrite the equation in the form of (a*x)^2 + k = 0, where k is a constant. To do this, we can move the 'bx' term to the right side of the equation and then square half of 'b' to get a perfect square on the left side.\n\n   ax^2 + bx + c = 0\n   => ax^2 + bx = -c\n   => (a*x)^2 + 2*(a*b/2)*x = -c*(a^2)\n\n2. Now, we complete the square by adding and subtracting (b/2a)^2 on both sides of the equation.\n\n   (a*x)^2 + 2*(a*b/2)*x + (b/2a)^2 - (b/2a)^2 = -c*(a^2) + (b/2a)^2\n   => (a*x + b/2a)^2 = -c*(a^2) + (b/2a)^2\n\n3. Take the square root of both sides. Remember that when we take the square root of a number, we get two solutions, one positive and one negative.\n\n   a*x + b/2a = \u00b1 \u221a(-c*(a^2) + (b/2a)^2)\n\n4. Solve for x by isolating the x term on one side of the equation.\n\n   a*x = \u00b1 \u221a(-c*(a^2) + (b/2a)^2) - b/2a\n   => x = \u00b1 \u221a(-c*(a^2) + (b/2a)^2) / a - b / (2a^2)\n\n5. Since there are two solutions, we have the quadratic formula:\n\n   x = (-b \u00b1 \u221a(b^2 - 4ac)) / (2a)\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 10\nV (Verbal Fluency): 10\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 10\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 10\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 10\nY (Affective Modeling): 0 (This task does not require affective modeling)\nF (Flexibility): 10\nD (Depth of Processing): 10",
